  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1290053666" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1290053666" />
    <a title="Debbie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8665845-debbie"><img alt="Debbie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1334166735p2/8665845.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1290053666?book_show_action=true">Jan 06, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Debbie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Debbie" href="/user/show/8665845-debbie">Debbie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8665845-debbie?shelf=title-love">title-love</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8665845-debbie?shelf=favorite-memoirs">favorite-memoirs</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8665845-debbie?shelf=favorite-authors">favorite-authors</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8665845-debbie?shelf=head-disorders">head-disorders</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8665845-debbie?shelf=all-time-favorites">all-time-favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8665845-debbie?shelf=luscious-spines-live-in-my-bookcase">luscious-spines-live-in-my-bookcase</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8665845-debbie?shelf=funny">funny</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8665845-debbie?shelf=2020-best-reads">2020-best-reads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8665845-debbie?shelf=bookcase-of-faves-at-home">bookcase-of-faves-at-home</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1290053666" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18397288277940143112"><b>Bring on the madness—it has me hoppin’!</b><br/><br/><i>“Other people might battle a subconscious fear of adversity, failure, or being stoned to death, but my hidden phobia makes me faint at the sight of outerwear.”</i><br/><br/>Hard to resist, huh? This off-kilter memoir had me riding on my pogo stick while howling deliriously. A comic genius, this Lawson person.<br/><br/>My daughter gave me this book on Christmas Day. I hardly read hard copies anymore because the print is too small, so for about 5 seconds I wasn’t thrilled. Then I op</span>
  <span id="freeText18397288277940143112" style="display:none"><b>Bring on the madness—it has me hoppin’!</b><br /><br /><i>“Other people might battle a subconscious fear of adversity, failure, or being stoned to death, but my hidden phobia makes me faint at the sight of outerwear.”</i><br /><br />Hard to resist, huh? This off-kilter memoir had me riding on my pogo stick while howling deliriously. A comic genius, this Lawson person.<br /><br />My daughter gave me this book on Christmas Day. I hardly read hard copies anymore because the print is too small, so for about 5 seconds I wasn’t thrilled. Then I opened it. Oh, the fun began! I immediately started reading about Lawson driving through a pick-up-meds line and seeing a box of dog biscuits in the window, and then seeing a guy putting his hand into the box and eating one!! Right then, my body froze but my whole soul was in hysterics. This was like getting swept up into a laugh-snort vortex. I read on:<br /><br /><i>“And then I thought, ‘Wait. Am I high right now? Is he high? Am I being tested? Should I say something?’ But I’m pretty sure you’re not supposed to accuse the man giving you drugs of eating dog food.”</i><br /><br />But this isn’t the end of it. I can’t transcribe the whole chapter though I am tempted. Suffice it to say, she doesn’t leave it alone. She ponders all the possible reasons he is eating dog biscuits and all the possible things she could do about it. She goes nuts with it, and I’m in hysterics, oblivious to the ohs and ahs of the fam opening other presents. I was the obnoxious one in the corner, demanding that my daughter listen as I read the chapter aloud. I couldn’t help myself. The hell with the other presents! I was intensely focused on the dog-biscuit-eating pharmacist! Who could NOT be?<br /><br />Lawson has a magic mix: she has a keen sense of the absurd, a severe case of anxiety, extreme curiosity, an over-active imagination, a big dose of self-deprecation, and uncontested writing chops. Put it all in the pot, stir for a minute, and voila—what comes out is pure gold.<br /><br />She goes all over the place and I follow her like a puppy. I’m in love with anyone who picks up on absurdities and knows how to turn them into copy. My favorite stories involve intruders at her Japanese hotel room, gall bladder pain, a facial, a sleep study, and a visit to Down Under, complete with koala, kangaroo, and rock tales. What I love is that she takes something odd that’s happening and runs with it, analyzing it to death, her phenomenal imagination churning out more and more possible scenarios and motivations. It’s reality at its most off-kilter. Her saint of a husband plays the straight man in her stories, and their conversations are a riot.<br /><br />Chapter titles are a gas, too. Here are a few: It’s Like Your Pants Are Bragging at Me; It’s Hard to Tell Which of Us Is Mentally Ill; George Washington’s Dildo; Things I May Have Accidentally Said During Uncomfortable Silences; Voodoo Vagina. Oh, I could go on, but this review is already too long.<br /><br />It’s not all fun and games. Lawson battles depression, I mean big-time depression. She also has severe anxiety. Writing helps her fight both. Some of her followers have similar issues, and that helps her feel good about herself, that she’s not alone and that her stories help others. In this memoir, she goes into the nitty-gritty of how it feels being her, living with mental illness. It’s very sad and very honest (she makes herself so vulnerable), and her perseverance and struggles are inspiring. <br /><br />Much of what she worries about is unique to her, and I can’t relate. But then there are these half-relates. Okay, so we both have a fear of flying. I have run-of-the-mill fear of flying, where I white-knuckle it through a flight. But her fear of flying is beautifully twisted: For her, the fear all takes place BEFORE she gets on the plane—the eternal trip to the airport and through the airport. Once she’s on the plane, she’s just fine. I love its backward-ness. <br /><br />And although I can’t relate to many of her stories (liking to wear a koala costume when visiting koalas, for example), I had a real woo-woo moment when reading the book. And it was about the strangest thing. Here goes (and you’ll see how weird I am, lol): Every time I see a plastic garbage bag on the road, I worry that there’s a dead baby or a body part inside. On the road the other day, I indeed saw the dreaded bag in the road, and I wondered (not for the first time) if I could write a story, a thriller, about it. My mind was churning. I came home and picked up the book. The chapter was about how she thinks garbage bags on the road have body parts in them!! How can this be? <br /><br />I love this book to death, but really, I don’t think it’s for everyone—the weird and wild are a bit much sometimes, and now and then it seems like she’s trying too hard. There were several chapters that I didn’t think were funny. Her dad was a taxidermist, and she is pretty obsessed with real “stuffed” animals—those stories didn’t entertain me. She got dressed up in a koala and then a kangaroo costume when she went to Australia. Again, that didn’t tickle my funny bone. I just figure you don’t like every single joke that a stand-up comic tells; there has to be an occasional miss. Mild and spotty irritation: she uses “totally” and “like” sometimes, which is weird because she ain’t no valley girl. I just chalked it up to the fact that she’s younger, and youngin’s sometimes talk funny. Another minor complaint: When she quotes her husband or her friend, their voices and ideas sound just like her own. They can’t possibly be as funny and odd as she is, so it stood out a little to hear extra Jennies. <br /><br />Sample funnies:<br /><br /><i>“I hate picnics. If god wanted us the eat on the ground he wouldn’t have invented couches.” <br /><br />“Too much grass and not enough birth control: that’s how goats are made.”</i> <br /><br />I read Lawson’s first book, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/12868761.Let_s_Pretend_This_Never_Happened_A_Mostly_True_Memoir" title="Let's Pretend This Never Happened A Mostly True Memoir by Jenny Lawson" rel="nofollow noopener">Let's Pretend This Never Happened: A Mostly True Memoir</a>, and I liked it. It had too much about her dad the taxidermist, though. I found this one funnier.<br /><br />I’m into another book but I’m missing being inside Jenny Lawson’s strange and wonderful head. This book, oh this book. A hard act to follow. Onto my All-Time Favorites list it goes!</span>
  <a data-text-id="18397288277940143112" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


