<div id="review_1468593464" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1468593464" />
    <a title="Derek" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13257456-derek"><img alt="Derek" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1348963993p2/13257456.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1468593464?book_show_action=true">Dec 14, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Derek" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Derek" href="/user/show/13257456-derek">Derek</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1468593464" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4354062510360084292">I&apos;m sorry that Jenny Lawson got dealt a bad hand in life, but honestly, she is a terrible writer. This book is filled with completely uninteresting anecdotes about falling asleep on her arms and them going numb that I thought would somehow tie into her daily struggle. but no that was it. Hilarious. There are several one-liners that would be cute little twitter posts, but listed out in a book is simply tedious. Moreover, the insights into mental illness are so superficial that only people who are</span>
  <span id="freeText4354062510360084292" style="display:none">I'm sorry that Jenny Lawson got dealt a bad hand in life, but honestly, she is a terrible writer. This book is filled with completely uninteresting anecdotes about falling asleep on her arms and them going numb that I thought would somehow tie into her daily struggle. but no that was it. Hilarious. There are several one-liners that would be cute little twitter posts, but listed out in a book is simply tedious. Moreover, the insights into mental illness are so superficial that only people who are dealing with something similar would appreciate, but it doesn't provide much for people on the outside to grasp to make sense of the world these people inhabit. The section on self-harming was pretty serious, but I didn't get anything from it other than it sucks. <br /><br />But the most severe crime which made the book un-finish-able for me is that it isn't funny whatsoever. The jokes are clumsy and obvious, the pop culture references forced, and the "wackiness" is just annoying. Ultimately, a lot of the book feels like a cross between a pitch session for a terrible sitcom and someone's therapy journal that hasn't seen any kind of revising or editing. Moreover, she seems almost proud of the fact that she's perfectly content to not do any work and just pump out writing whenever she feels like it. It proves to be a thesis statement for the book itself.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4354062510360084292" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


